<img src="https://biz-file.com/c/1908/512382-625x325.jpg?2" alt="Appliance and electronics shopping grows nearly 50% since 2016" width="625" height="325">©Sergey Ryzhov via 123RFThe findings are based on in-depth interviews conducted with over 18,200 women from a diverse range of communities, states the company.Upward growth trajectory since 2016<img src="https://biz-file.com/c/1908/512379.jpg" alt="Appliance and electronics shopping grows nearly 50% since 2016" width="620" height="363">According to Spark Media, these findings underscore that while national statistics might paint an informative picture at the macro-level, it’s the area by area focus that holds significant insights into how women are living, what their needs are and what they’re willing to spend money on.The report reveals that residential living circumstances impact considerably on appliance and electronics purchases. <img src="https://biz-file.com/c/1906/504294.jpg" alt="#ROOTS2019 sheds light on buyer behaviour" width="120" height="120">#ROOTS2019 sheds light on buyer behaviourBuilding brands, looking for opportunities to talk to potential buyers or product users by geographic area and potentially influencing behaviour. This works best when we understand what makes consumers tick...Issued by Spark Media 28 Jun 2019For example, Midrand has seen a boom in apartment residency rates, with much of the property appealing to young professionals sharing accommodation to lessen the burden of rent. These individuals prioritise smaller sized appliances and home electronics to maximise space savings. Compact and portable devices are preferred.A large family that shares a space in Soweto, by contrast, determines size primarily by the amount of people the appliance needs to serve on a regular basis.Investment purchasesAnother significant consideration when trying to predict possible spending patterns is confidence in future income and employment. In economically uncertain times, electronics and appliances are increasingly looked at as longer term investments.<img src="https://biz-file.com/c/1906/501285-120x120.jpg?2" alt="Debbie McIntyre, marketing and research director at Spark Media. Image supplied." width="120" height="120">#Roots2019: Brand loyalty is deadBrands like to think that everyone loves their brand, but the harsh reality is that while they use your brand, they also use everyone else's brands...By Danette Breitenbach 12 Jun 2019The 2019 sample is one that has become accustomed to Black Friday, which only started gaining traction in 2016. It is plausible that the annual sale has fostered a new buying culture: i.e. a tangible goal that comes round once a year and can be saved towards.